Why do we need statistical
inference in science?
Statistical Inference
- Can’t study the whole population
- How do we prove something?
- Example: does drug X increase amount of sleep
students get?
Can’t study the whole population
Obtain a representative
sample of your population
Statistical Inference
- Test drug X in a sample of students
- How can we be certain difference in amount of sleep is
related to the drug and not random chance?
- Many models/statistical tests attempt to show certain
relationships exist
- R makes it easier to analyze data for relationships and
display results

Variables
Variables
- Placeholders
- Store information
Example:
- X = 5
- X + 4
- Will be equal to 9
Variables in R
Syntax:
variable_name <- variable_value
variable_name = variable_value
- variable_name must be 1 continuous sequence of
letters/symbols (no spaces)
- Can add underscores in between words
- R is CASE-SENSITIVE
Variables in R: Examples
Syntax:
variable_name <- variable_value
- five <- 5
- print(five)
- data <- dataset_name
- print(data)
Your Turn: R dataset sleep

- Print data
Syntax Hints
variable_name <- variable_value
print(variable_name)
Sleep as a variable called data
Variable
name
Value to be stored
in variable
Can use variable name like
the value stored inside
Notes on variable names
Syntax:
variable_name <- variable_value
- variable_name has to be unique
- X <- 1
- X <- 2
- X <- 3
- You have lost the first two assignments to X
- X stores the number 3
Notes on variable values
Syntax:
variable_name <- variable_value
- variable_value can be just about anything
- Numbers
- num <- 4
- Characters/words: surround with “quotes”
- word <- “DNA”
- Other variables
- word2 <- word

Syntax Hints
variable_name <- variable_value
print(variable_name)
Why use variables?
- Save time
- Can change value of variable without changing
how that variable is used
- Creates copy of that value
- Modify data and still have the original sleep
dataset
Order of Operations
Order of Operations
- PEMDAS
- Parentheses ()
- Exponents (^)
- Multiplication (*) & division (/)
- Addition (+) & subtraction (-)
- precedence from left to right

Vectors
Vector
- Elements of the same type concatenated together
- Like a list
Syntax:
c(element1, element2, element3, etc)
- Examples:
- c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
- c(1)
- c(“Male”, “Female”,”Male”,”Female”)

variable_name <- variable_value
c(element1, element2, element3, etc)
Vectors and Variables
- Can assign vectors to variables
- classmates <- c(“student1”, “student2”, “student3”)
- Can print the variable
- print(classmates)

Vectors and Datasets
Syntax:
dataset_name$column_name
- Gives me a vector for that column
- Examples:
- sleep$extra
- sleep$group
- sleep$ID
Your Turn: All Topics Applied

- Create variable sleep_difference_minutes that stores a vector
of the sleep differences in minutes
- (Need to multiply each number of hours in extra by 60)

Multiplication: *
All Topics Applied
- How to access extra vector from sleep dataset?
- sleep$extra
- How to convert hours to minutes?
- sleep$extra * 60
- How to store that result in a new variable?
- sleep_difference_minutes <- sleep$extra * 60
- Can print sleep_difference_minutes to check
- Not required:
- sleep$sleep_different_minutes <- sleep$extra * 60
- Stores this new vector into the sleep dataset (as a 4th column)
